, <link>
James H. Hester</link>, <link>
Cheng F. Ng</link>, <link>
Debra A. (Lelewer) Brum</link>, <link>
Lynn M. Stauffer</link>, <link>
Steven S. Seiden</link>, and <link>
Jonathan Kent Martin</link>.</p>
<p>

He is best known for his 1975 and 1977 work on the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../105/236105.xml">
longest common subsequence problem</link>: <event wordnetid="100029378" confidence="0.8">
<rule wordnetid="105846932" confidence="0.8">
<act wordnetid="100030358" confidence="0.8">
<psychological_feature wordnetid="100023100" confidence="0.8">
<procedure wordnetid="101023820" confidence="0.8">
<activity wordnetid="100407535" confidence="0.8">
<algorithm wordnetid="105847438" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../509/10171509.xml">
Hirschberg's algorithm</link></algorithm>
</activity>
</procedure>
</psychological_feature>
</act>
</rule>
</event>
 for this problem and for the related string edit distance problem solves it efficiently in only linear space. He is also known for his work in several other areas, including <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../501/8501.xml">
 Distributed Algorithms</link>. In <peer wordnetid="109626238" confidence="0.8">
<physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
